{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507195"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:50:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:50:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2610"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2610"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.33,0.4,0.16,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2610"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84123"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"813"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35275"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with increasing difficulty using his left hand. He has noticed that over the past two years that he cannot straighten his fingers easily, particularly his ring finger (image). Initially, he used to rub his palm to get his finger \u0022unstuck\u0022 but his symptoms have worsened now. He does not report any pain. He retired as a schoolteacher six years ago and now spends most of his time painting and doing various house maintenance jobs. His medical history includes diabetes mellitus for the past 25 years and he is currently on metformin and insulin. He smoked cigarettes for five years during his college but quit after graduation. He drinks 1 glass of alcohol every day. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His physical examination is unremarkable apart from the changes in his left hand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors in this patient is most likely to be associated with the examination finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trauma","Chronic alcohol consumption","Diabetes","Occupation","Smoking"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s examination finding of the hand shows Dupuytren\u0027s contracture (DC). This is a disorder characterised by progressive fibrosis of the palmar fascia. There is probably a hereditary component and the condition appears to be more common in patients with diabetes, alcoholism, smoking, or chronic illnesses. Although DC can present with no identifiable underlying cause (it is most commonly idiopathic), the most likely \u003Cem\u003Eassociation\u003C/em\u003E in this specific patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetes mellitus. \u003C/strong\u003EDC is more common in patients with adult-onset diabetes and patients with blood sugar levels corresponding to moderate diabetes. This may be due to the increased accumulation of advanced glycosylated end products (AGEs) in patients with diabetes, although further research work to clarify this relationship is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral studies have shown an association of DC with \u003Cstrong\u003Etrauma\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccupations\u003C/strong\u003E which involve repetitive handling tasks or vibrations. However, this association remains controversial and are unlikely to be have major factors in this patient\u0027s case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDC may develop in patients with excessive weekly \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcohol \u003C/strong\u003Eor long history of \u003Cstrong\u003Esmoking\u003C/strong\u003E. However, neither this patient\u0027s weekly alcohol consumption is high, nor does he have a long smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn association of epilepsy and antiepileptic drugs with DC has been suggested. However, it has not been confirmed in most studies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dupuytren\u0027s contracture is associated with several risk factors including genetics,  ethnicity, sex, alcoholism, and smoking."],"references":["Aggarwal R, Blazar PE. Dupuytren\u0027s contracture. In: UptoDate. Waltham (MA); 2021. [updated 2020 Mar; cited 2021 Jul 13]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/dupuytrens-contracture","Stewart BD, Nascimento AF. Palmar and plantar fibromatosis: a review. J Path Transl Med 2021; 55: 265-70.","Ganesan S, Tantone RP, Komatsu DE, Hurst LC. The prevalence of Dupuytren\u0027s disease in patients with diabetes mellitus. Commun Med (Lond). 2023 Jul 13;3(1):96. doi: 10.1038/s43856-023-00332-7. PMID: 37443309; PMCID: PMC10345101. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37443309/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84123"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2610"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14573"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14573"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cd3fc525-c8d2-4bde-bbb7-6aed53e6ac3c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cd3fc525-c8d2-4bde-bbb7-6aed53e6ac3c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":497,"height":400}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84123","l